ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescence stability of the p-CQDs was studied under different conditions of ionic strengths, pH ranges, continuous photoirradiation as well as long-time storage. On irradiation of light at 540 nm on the p-CQDs under various ionic strength conditions between 0 and 2 M KCl, no significant difference in the fluorescence intensities was observed, as shown in Fig. 5
                        a. Fluorescence stability studies was performed under different pH values between 1 and 12 (Fig. 5b). It is evident that the PL intensities of the p-CQDs decreased considerably only under extremely acidic and highly alkaline conditions, while the PL intensities remained almost unaffected under all the other pH values. This pH-dependent PL behavior could be ascribed to the reversible protonation and deprotonation of the oxygen-bearing surface functionalities of the p-CQDs, which could alter their energy levels. Nevertheless, this justification is yet controversial because the PL characteristics of CQDs vary in different situations [36]. At low pH values, protonation of the acidic and amine functionalities at the surface of the p-CQDs increases the H-bonding associations in p-CQDs. This results in the aggregation of the particles and the consequent reduction in the PL intensity [37–39]. At higher pH values, the deprotonation of the carboxyl, hydroxyl, and amino functional groups could reduce their vibrational coupling and H-bonding interactions and result in a decrease in the PL intensities of the p-CQDs [40]. Also, good PL stability of the p-CQDs in aqueous medium in a wide pH range between 2 and 9 suggests their promising applications in numerous fields. It was also observed that the p-CQDs on continued irradiation of light at 540 nm for 60 min, had no notable effects on the PL intensity, as shown in Fig. 5c. Furthermore, the homogeneous aqueous solution of the p-CQDs was found to be stable on long-term storage. The p-CQDs on photoirradiation at 540 nm displayed no striking changes in the PL intensities for 120 days, which accounts for its long-term stability as shown in Fig. 5d. The value of zeta potential obtained for the p-CQDs at pH 7 was −27.4 mV (Fig. 6
                        ). This negative value can be attributed to the presence of carbonyl and hydroxyl groups on the p-CQDs surface. The above results indicate good PL stability of the p-CQDs.
